{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"PASS 1 review — criterion T8 (LLM/prompt structural-completeness probe). This plan defines an LLM/agent review system (G3/G4 container reviewers, a structured `plan_review_findings` output schema, and S4's \"merge G3+G4 into one call\" + S5's \"bin-pack children\" prompt restructurings), so T8 applies. Findings + affirmations below; tool-verified against the live container/finder code.\n\nAFFIRMATIONS (T8 checklist items this plan satisfies):\n- Referenced agents/seams/enums EXIST and are real (no pink-elephant): `_run_container` (pass1.py:114), `pass1_container` (passes.py:241), the shared `RunRequest`/runner seam + `_anthropic_cache_settings` (runner.py:209-222,421-435), `output_schema=\"plan_review_findings\"` (passes.py:209,268), the eval_specs suite (eval_specs/*.eval.yaml) and `parity.py` are all present and named.\n- FALLBACK for a failed sub-step IS specified for the EXISTING path: warm-pairing systemic failure aborts the tier; non-systemic warm failure degrades to direct fan-out with the failed pairing re-run in the pool (no silent drop); per-pairing pool failure drops only that pairing's findings (pass1.py:171-241). S6 also specifies an eval fallback posture (offline discipline blocks; live eval opt-in/non-blocking).\n- No ambiguous counter/state increment in the plan-level spec: the cost-model/budget-cap fix is described as \"never shed G3/G4\" + \"fix the cost model\" (not centrality scaling), which is unambiguous at plan grain.\n\nFINDINGS:\n\n- [ ] S4 (\"merge G3+G4 into one call per bin\") changes the per-call criterion vocabulary from ONE criterion to TWO, but the plan never specifies the FINDING→CRITERION ATTRIBUTION PROTOCOL for the merged call (how the merged prompt instructs the model to tag each finding G3-vs-G4 in the structured `criteria` field, and the keep/drop rule). State this protocol in S4.\n  criteria: [T8]\n  location: \"Children\" item 4 (S4) + Remediation \"merge G3+G4 into one call per bin\"; AC \"Findings remain within offline-eval tolerance\"; ticket comment \"G3/G4-attribution accuracy\" (S6 metric)\n  evidence: [\"The existing single-criterion path (`pass1_container`, passes.py:241-270) passes ONE `criterion` and so cannot mis-attribute. The MULTI-criterion finder path proves attribution is load-bearing: passes.py:214-224 keeps ONLY findings whose model-returned `criteria` intersect the in-chunk ids and DROPS the rest — with an explicit warning that the old `or ids[:1]` fallback 'silently mis-attributed it to the chunk's first criterion, corrupting the finding→criterion mapping the coach + sidecar depend on' (passes.py:217-220).\", \"S6's own AC requires reporting 'G3/G4-attribution accuracy' — i.e. attribution is a measured success dimension — yet the plan text gives no protocol the executor must implement to produce a correctly-attributed merged finding set.\", \"ABSENCE: no S4 description text in the plan specifies the merged-call prompt's per-criterion tagging instruction or the post-call keep/drop/attribution rule.\"]\n  suggested_fix: \"In S4, specify that the merged G3+G4 prompt requires each finding to carry the exact criterion id (G3 or G4) in `criteria`, and that the post-call handler mirrors the finder's discipline (passes.py:222): keep only findings whose `criteria` ⊆ {G3,G4}, never fabricate an attribution to a default criterion.\"\n\n- [ ] The \"REQUIRED structured per-child output guardrail\" that S6's review notes is ESSENTIAL and \"must also apply to S4\" is referenced but its SCHEMA/PROTOCOL is never co-located with (or defined in) the plan — specify the guardrail's shape (the per-child structured output it enforces) where S4/S5 use it.\n  criteria: [T8]\n  location: \"Children\" items 4-5 (S4 merge / S5 bin-pack); ticket comment (1782572466917749001) \"the REQUIRED structured per-child output guardrail (already in S5) is ESSENTIAL and must also apply to S4\"\n  evidence: [\"When children are batched (S4 merge / S5 bin-pack), multiple children share ONE call; the meta-review of this very epic observed TAIL children get shallower review (recency/salience bias) and concluded a structured per-child output guardrail is required to force per-child coverage. The plan text names no such guardrail and does not define its schema (e.g. a required finding-or-explicit-clean entry per child id) — a processing rule referenced but not co-located with the schema that needs it.\", \"ABSENCE: the plan's S5 line is only 'child bin-packing' and S4 is only 'merge G3+G4 into one call per bin'; neither states the per-child completeness guarantee or its structured shape.\"]\n  suggested_fix: \"Specify in S4/S5 that each batched call must return a structured per-child result keyed by child ticket_id (a finding list OR an explicit 'clean' marker per child), so a batched call cannot silently omit a tail child; have S6's eval check tail-child recall against this guarantee.\"\n\n- [ ] Specify the FALLBACK when a merged/packed call exceeds the window in S4/S5 — the existing too-big rule fires per (parent+ONE child) pairing (pass1.py:146-150); merging criteria and packing multiple children per call changes the pairing size and the per-criterion/per-child failure granularity, which the plan leaves unspecified.\n  criteria: [T8]\n  location: \"Children\" items 4-5 (S4/S5); Remediation; Sequencing note (\"S4/S5's sizing.py container-cost projections\")\n  evidence: [\"Today an oversized pairing becomes a DET 'too-big' failure finding (pass1.py:149-150, `_too_big_finding`) at single-child granularity. A merged G3+G4 / multi-child bin raises the bin's token size and conflates failure attribution: if a packed bin is too big or its call fails, the plan does not say whether it (a) splits the bin, (b) emits a single too-big finding, or (c) attributes the failure across the merged criteria / packed children.\", \"ABSENCE: no S4/S5 text defines the incomplete-bin fallback or how a per-bin failure maps back to specific (criterion, child) results.\"]\n  suggested_fix: \"In S5, define a deterministic bin-split/fallback (e.g. on too-big or call failure, re-run the bin's children as smaller bins / per-child pairings) so no child or criterion is silently dropped; in S4 state how a merged-call failure is recorded against both G3 and G4.\""},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782578526685470001,"uuid":"cd014541-8dfc-436d-af2b-f011311db8a5"}